Java 8 features:

1. Lambda Expressions: Anonymous functions (no name, no class)
    Why: Reduce boilerplate code (especially in collections, threads)
    Syntax: (parameter) -> expression
    // Before Java 8
      Runnable r = new Runnable() {
          public void run() {
              System.out.println("Hello");
          }
      };
    // Java 8
    Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Hello");
    Real Usage: Sorting, Iteration and Thread execution

2. Functional Interfaces: Interface with only one abstract method
    @FunctionalInterface
    interface MyFunc {
        void execute();   // only one abstract method
    }
    ✔ Can have: multiple default methods , multiple static methods
   ❌ Cannot have: more than one abstract method
    Why: They enable: ✅ Lambda expressions ✅ Method references ✅ Clean, readable code
    Common Examples: Runnable, Callable and Comparator
   
Built-in Functional Interfaces:
  1. Predicate<T> :Represents a condition (boolean check)
      Method: boolean test(T t);
      Predicate<Integer> isEven = x -> x % 2 == 0;
      System.out.println(isEven.test(4)); // true
 
BiPredicate<T, U> - Takes 2 inputs
      BiPredicate<Integer, Integer> p = (a, b) -> a > b;
      p.test(5, 3); // true
      Default Methods (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)
          p.and(p2)     // both true
          p.or(p2)      // any one true
          p.negate()    // reverse
use case: list.stream() .filter(x -> x > 10);

2. Function<T, R> - Transform input → output
    Method : R apply(T t);
    Types / Variants
        ✔ BiFunction<T, U, R> : BiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        ✔ UnaryOperator<T> (Same input & output type) - UnaryOperator<Integer> square = x -> x * x;
        ✔ BinaryOperator<T> - BinaryOperator<Integer> sum = (a, b) -> a + b;
       Default Methods
          f.andThen(g)   // first f, then g
          f.compose(g)   // first g, then f

          Function<Integer, Integer> f1 = x -> x * 2;
          Function<Integer, Integer> f2 = x -> x + 3;
          System.out.println(f1.andThen(f2).apply(5)); // 13
          System.out.println(f1.compose(f2).apply(5)); // 16
         Real Use: list.stream().map(x -> x * 2);

        Function is a functional interface, and identity() is a static method inside it.
        static <T> Function<T, T> identity()
        When you want: element itself as key or value and  No transformation needed

3. Consumer<T> - Consumes input → no return
     Method: void accept(T t);
      Consumer<String> c = x -> System.out.println(x);
      c.accept("Hello");
    ✔ BiConsumer<T, U> -BiConsumer<String, Integer> c = (name, age) -> System.out.println(name + " " + age);
      Default Method - c.andThen(c2)
      Consumer<String> c1 = x -> System.out.println("Hello " + x);
      Consumer<String> c2 = x -> System.out.println("Bye " + x);
      c1.andThen(c2).accept("Java");
       Real Use :list.forEach(System.out::println);

4. Supplier<T> - No input → returns value
     Method - T get();
      Supplier<Double> s = () -> Math.random();
      System.out.println(s.get());
      Real Use: Supplier<List<String>> listSupplier = ArrayList::new;

