3. Stream API : A Stream is a sequence of data used to perform operations (like filter, map, sort) in a functional style.
                It does NOT store data
                It works on collections (List, Set, etc.)
                It processes data lazily
    why: Cleaner + faster (parallel processing)

    Collection → Stream → Intermediate Ops → Terminal Op → Result

    Types of Operations:
     1. Intermediate Operations
           Return a new stream
           Lazy (executed only when terminal op runs)
        Common Methods:
        ✔ filter (Predicate) - stream.filter(x -> x > 10);
        ✔ map (Function) -stream.map(x -> x * 2);
        ✔ sorted -  stream.sorted();  stream.sorted((a,b) -> b - a);
        ✔ distinct - stream.distinct();
        ✔ limit / skip - stream.limit(3); and stream.skip(2);
        ✔ flatMap:
                List<List<Integer>> list = Arrays.asList(
                    Arrays.asList(1,2),
                    Arrays.asList(3,4));
                list.stream()
                    .flatMap(x -> x.stream())
                    .forEach(System.out::println);
         peek()- for debugging

   2. Terminal Operations - Produce result / end stream
        ✔ forEach (Consumer)- stream.forEach(System.out::println);
        ✔ collect - stream.collect(Collectors.toList());
        ✔ count - long c = stream.count();
        ✔ findFirst -  stream.findFirst(); Returns first element (order matters)
           findAny-Returns any element (optimized for parallel)                
        ✔ anyMatch / allMatch / noneMatch - stream.anyMatch(x -> x > 10);
              anyMatch()- Returns true if ANY element matches
              allMatch()- Returns true if ALL elements match
              noneMatch()- Returns true if NO element matches
        ✔ reduce - int sum = list.stream().reduce(0, (a, b) -> a + b);

Collectors Methods - stream.collect(...)
✔ toList() - stream.collect(Collectors.toList());
✔ toSet() - stream.collect(Collectors.toSet());
✔ toMap() - stream.collect(Collectors.toMap( x -> x, x -> x.length());
✔ groupingBy() -Collectors.groupingBy(Function.identity())
              Map<String, List<Employee>> map = employees.stream()
                          .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDept));
✔ partitioningBy() -Collectors.partitioningBy(x -> x > 10);
