1. Can we throw exceptions in Streams? ✔ Unchecked Exceptions (RuntimeException)
    list.stream()
        .map(x -> {
            if (x == 0) throw new RuntimeException("Zero not allowed");
            return 10 / x;
        })
        .forEach(System.out::println);
        ✔ Works fine
        ✔ No compiler error

    ❌ Checked Exceptions 👉 NOT directly allowed ❌
    Example
    list.stream()
        .map(x -> {
            return someMethod(x); // throws IOException
        });👉 Compiler error:Unhandled exception type IOException
 2. Why Checked Exceptions Don’t Work?
      Because functional interfaces like: Function<T,R>, Predicate<T> and Consumer<T> 👉 DO NOT declare throws Exception
      Example: R apply(T t);   // no throws

 3. Ways to Handle Checked Exceptions in Streams
  1. Try-Catch inside Lambda (Most Common)
      list.stream()
          .map(x -> {
              try {
                  return someMethod(x);
              } catch (IOException e) {
                  throw new RuntimeException(e); // wrap
              }
          })
          .forEach(System.out::println);
  2. Wrap into Runtime Exception
        public String safeMethod(int x) {
            try {
                return someMethod(x);
            } catch (IOException e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        }
    Usage:  list.stream()
        .map(this::safeMethod)
        .forEach(System.out::println);
 3. Custom Functional Interface (Advanced 🔥)
        @FunctionalInterface
        interface ThrowingFunction<T, R> {
            R apply(T t) throws Exception;
        }
    Wrapper:
      static <T, R> Function<T, R> wrap(ThrowingFunction<T, R> f) {
          return x -> {
              try {
                  return f.apply(x);
              } catch (Exception e) {
                  throw new RuntimeException(e);
              }
          };
      }

Usage:  list.stream()
        .map(wrap(x -> someMethod(x)))
        .forEach(System.out::println);
 4. Using Optional (Clean Approach)
      list.stream()
          .map(x -> {
              try {
                  return Optional.of(someMethod(x));
              } catch (Exception e) {
                  return Optional.empty();
              }
          })
          .filter(Optional::isPresent)
          .map(Optional::get)
          .forEach(System.out::println);

  Parallel Stream:
      Processes stream using multiple threads (ForkJoinPool)
      Multi-core processing
      list.parallelStream() OR list.stream().parallel()
      list.parallelStream()
          .forEach(System.out::println);

  Internal Working:
          Uses ForkJoinPool.commonPool()
          Splits data into chunks
          Processes in parallel
          Merges results

   Parallel vs Sequential Stream:
        Feature	            Sequential	          Parallel
        Threads	            Single	              Multiple
        Order	              Maintained          	Not guaranteed
        Performance	        Slower	              Faster (large data)
        Debugging          	Easy	                Hard
  
  Important Rules:
        ❌ Avoid Parallel Stream when: Small dataset,  Shared mutable data and Order is important
        ✔ Use Parallel when: Large dataset, Independent operations and CPU intensive
    Dangerous Example:
          List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();          
          list.parallelStream().forEach(result::add); // ❌ NOT SAFE 👉 Causes: Race conditions and Data inconsistency

Parallel Stream Exception Behavior 👉 If exception occurs: Stream terminates and Exception is propagated
      list.parallelStream()
          .forEach(x -> {
              if (x == 5) throw new RuntimeException("Error");
          });

